$MU The impact of China banning Micron chips on the company is expected to be quite limited. This is because Micron's major customers in China are consumer electronics firms such as smartphone and computer manufacturers, not infrastructure suppliers. Most of its revenue in China is not generated from telcos and the government, but rather from these electronics firms. Thus, while the ban may affect a segment of their business, it isn't anticipated to have a severe impact on their overall revenue.  
  
It's worth noting that Micron generates about 10% of its revenue from China. In 2022, the company generated $5.2 billion of revenue from China and Hong Kong, which is about 16% of its total revenue. A substantial portion of Micron's products that go to China are purchased by non-Chinese firms for use in products that are manufactured in the country. However, it's not clear how the ban will affect the company's sales to these non-Chinese customers in China​

$MU In 2022, Micron reported $3.3 billion in sales in China, roughly 11 percent of its annual $30.8 billion in global sales. It was unclear how much of those sales in China would be affected by the government's action. Also, it doesn't have manufacturing exposure in China. Yes, the news isn't great but exposure is limited.

$MRNA So on paper this is great news but there are many more nuances to it that doesn't help solve the short term problem. Unlike small molecule drugs that are easy to manufacture there is no thing as "Generic Vaccine" They are far more complex so let's say a new manufacturer in India wants to replicate the Pfizer/Biontech vaccine they will need to run its own clinical trials to prove they are safe. Moderna already waived its right to the patents back in October, the issue is technology transfer. So they need significant knowledge transfer and building those new plants takes a long time. Nevertheless it would help in long term supply. In summary key barrier to increasing capacity isn't patents but trade secrets, know how and scarce physical supplies - Info based on Stanford article.
